SIMPLE: humanity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Humanity
<hw>Hu*man"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Humanities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>humanitas</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>humanit⟦eacute⟧</ets>. See <er>Human</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being human; the peculiar nature of man,
by which he is distinguished from other beings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mankind collectively; the human race.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But hearing oftentimes⟦br⟧
The still, and music <qex>humanity</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a debt we owe to <qex>humanity</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>S. S.
Smith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The quality of being humane; the kind feelings,
dispositions, and sympathies of man; especially, a disposition to
relieve persons or animals in distress, and to treat all creatures with
kindness and tenderness.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The common offices of
<xex>humanity</xex> and friendship.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mental cultivation; liberal education; instruction
in classical and polite literature.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Polished with <qex>humanity</qex> and the study of witty
science.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> (With definite article) <def>The
branches of polite or elegant learning; as language, rhetoric, poetry,
and the ancient classics; belles-letters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The cultivation of the languages, literature, history,
and arch⟦ae⟧ology of Greece and Rome, were very commonly called
<xex>liter⟦ae⟧ humaniores</xex>, or, in English, the
<xex>humanities</xex>, . . . by way of opposition to the <xex>liter⟦ae⟧
divin⟦ae⟧</xex>, or divinity.</note> <rj><au>G. P. Marsh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humanization</ent>⟦br⟧
